-- FRAME 1: evaluate generate-article (soft cell, LLM) [iteration 0]
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- Ready set: { generate-article } — topic→title, topic→scope available
-- Blocked: { spawn-fact-checkers } — needs generate-article→claims
-- Blocked: all downstream (transitive)

⊢ generate-article
  given topic→title ≡ "The History of Version Control Systems"
  given topic→scope ≡ "From early mainframe source management through distributed version control..."
  yield article-text, claims[]

  ∴ Write a concise article (6-8 paragraphs) titled «topic→title»...

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield article-text ≡ "The History of Version Control Systems

Version control systems have been fundamental to software engineering since the earliest days of collaborative programming. The need to track changes, manage concurrent edits, and maintain a history of modifications drove the creation of increasingly sophisticated tools over five decades.

The earliest version control system was SCCS (Source Code Control System), created by Marc Rochkind at Bell Labs in 1972. SCCS introduced the concept of deltas — storing only the differences between file versions rather than complete copies. It operated on individual files and was designed for the Unix operating system. SCCS remained the dominant version control tool in Unix environments throughout the 1970s.

RCS (Revision Control System) was developed by Walter Tichy at Purdue University in 1982. RCS improved on SCCS by using reverse deltas — storing the most recent version in full and reconstructing older versions by applying patches backwards. This made accessing the latest version faster, which matched typical developer workflows. Like SCCS, RCS tracked individual files rather than project-wide changes.

CVS (Concurrent Versions System) was created by Dick Grune in 1986 and later rewritten by Brian Berliner in 1989. CVS was the first version control system to support concurrent editing by multiple developers on the same codebase. It introduced the copy-modify-merge workflow that would become standard. CVS used a central server architecture and operated on entire directory trees rather than individual files.

Subversion (SVN) was created by CollabNet in 2000 as an explicit replacement for CVS. The project was led by Karl Fogel and Jim Blandy. Subversion addressed CVS limitations by supporting atomic commits, directory versioning, and efficient branching through copy-on-write. Subversion 1.0 was released in February 2004.

BitKeeper was a proprietary distributed version control system created by Larry McVoy in 1998. It was notably used by the Linux kernel project from 2002 to 2005. BitKeeper pioneered distributed version control concepts including local commits and peer-to-peer synchronization. The revocation of BitKeeper's free license for Linux development in April 2005 directly precipitated the creation of Git.

Git was created by Linus Torvalds in April 2005 after the BitKeeper controversy. Git was designed for speed, data integrity, and support for distributed workflows. Its content-addressable storage model uses SHA-1 hashes to identify every object. Git achieved dominance in open-source development and became the most widely used version control system worldwide.

Mercurial was created by Matt Mackall and first released on April 19, 2005 — the same month as Git. Both projects were responses to the BitKeeper situation. Mercurial was designed with a focus on simplicity and performance for large repositories. While Mercurial gained significant adoption (notably by Mozilla and Facebook), Git ultimately achieved broader market dominance."

  yield claims ≡ [
    "SCCS was created by Marc Rochkind at Bell Labs in 1972.",
    "SCCS introduced the concept of deltas for storing file version differences.",
    "RCS was developed by Walter Tichy at Purdue University in 1982.",
    "RCS used reverse deltas, storing the most recent version in full.",
    "CVS was created by Dick Grune in 1986.",
    "CVS was rewritten by Brian Berliner in 1989.",
    "CVS was the first version control system to support concurrent editing by multiple developers.",
    "Subversion was created by CollabNet in 2000.",
    "The Subversion project was led by Karl Fogel and Jim Blandy.",
    "Subversion 1.0 was released in February 2004.",
    "BitKeeper was created by Larry McVoy in 1998.",
    "BitKeeper was used by the Linux kernel project from 2002 to 2005.",
    "The revocation of BitKeeper's free license occurred in April 2005.",
    "Git was created by Linus Torvalds in April 2005.",
    "Git uses SHA-1 hashes for content-addressable storage.",
    "Mercurial was created by Matt Mackall and first released on April 19, 2005."
  ]

-- oracle checks (aspirational under ⊢∘ — feedback only, do not block):
